│ Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe debug log shows:\n- SLP builds and schedules        │
│ bundles, then performs vectorization. It replaces uses in a number of places  │
│ and marks many instructions for deletion (via eraseInstruction and            │
│ removeInstructionsAndOperands). \n- During the insertelement shuffle          │
│ optimization, it creates a new vector/shuffle and marks insertelement chain   │
│ nodes with eraseInstruction(IE). Later                                        │
│ removeInstructionsAndOperands(RemovedInsts) marks and removes scalar nodes.   │
│ \n- The log shows \"Replaced:\" messages and then removal staging. \n- The    │
│ crash happens in BoUpSLP::~BoUpSLP when erasing the DeletedInstructions. In   │
│ the debugger, the failing instruction I is a shufflevector (named %3) with    │
│ getNumUses() == 1, located in bb1, i.e., it still has a user.\n\n3. Root      │
│ Cause Analysis:\nThe destructor currently asserts that every instruction in   │
│ DeletedInstructions has no remaining uses (use_empty()). This is valid if all │
│ users have been either replaced or themselves marked and processed for        │
│ deletion. Elsewhere in the pass (removeInstructionsAndOperands), LLVM         │
│ accounts for the case where an instruction being deleted may still be         │
│ referenced by other instructions also slated for deletion, by asserting a     │
│ weaker condition:\n  assert(I->use_empty() || all_of(I->uses(), [&](Use &U) { │
│ return isDeleted(cast<Instruction>(U.getUser())); }))\nThis allows removing   │
│ an instruction whose users are also in DeletedInstructions, and relies on a   │
│ later pass to null out operands and delete in order.\nHowever, the destructor │
│ uses the stronger assertion (I->use_empty()), not considering the legitimate  │
│ case that the user is also in DeletedInstructions. In this reproducer, a      │
│ shuffle left in DeletedInstructions still has a user also marked for          │
│ deletion, causing the assertion to fire even though the subsequent steps      │
│ would safely clean up.\nThus, the issue is an overly strict assertion and     │
│ deletion logic in the destructor that doesn't mirror the logic used by        │
│ removeInstructionsAndOperands. The first transformation point identified is   │
│ actually the erasure in the destructor; the mismatch in conditions is the     │
│ source of failure.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nModify BoUpSLP::~BoUpSLP at │
│ lines 4439-4443 to relax the assertion and use                                │
│ removeFromParent/SE->forgetValue similar to removeInstructionsAndOperands.    │
│ Specifically:\n- Replace the current assert(I->use_empty()) with a condition  │
│ that allows uses by instructions that are also marked for deletion.\n- Use    │
│ removeFromParent (not eraseFromParent) after dropAllReferences, and forget    │
│ the value in ScalarEvolution to maintain analysis                             │
│ correctness.\n\nEdit:\n4439:   for (auto *I : DeletedInstructions) {\n4440:   │
│ assert((I->use_empty() || all_of(I->uses(), [&](Use &U) {\n4441:              │
│ return DeletedInstructions.contains(cast<Instruction>(U.getUser()));\n4442:   │
│ })) && \"trying to erase instruction with users.\");\n4443:     if            │
│ (I->getParent()) { I->removeFromParent(); SE->forgetValue(I); } else { /* no  │
│ parent, nothing to remove */ }\n\nThis change mirrors the robust handling     │
│ already used in removeInstructionsAndOperands and prevents the destructor     │
│ from asserting in the legitimate case where users are also scheduled for      │
│ deletion. The dropAllReferences performed earlier ensures operands are        │
│ cleared and allows the recursive DCE that follows to safely clean up          │
│ remaining dead instructions.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy aligning the destructor's  │
│ deletion logic with the established removeInstructionsAndOperands semantics,  │
│ we avoid the false-positive assertion in cases where a to-be-deleted          │
│ instruction still has users that are also to be deleted. This ensures safe    │
│ cleanup without compromising the invariant that no live users remain. The     │
│ expected effect is that the pass cleans up DeadInsts and DeletedInstructions  │
│ without crashing on the given reproducer, while preserving correctness and    │
│ analyses."})                                                                  │
