│                                                                               │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The crash is an assertion failure in BoUpSLP::~BoUpSLP triggered when the     │
│ pass tries to erase an instruction that still has users. The reproducer shows │
│ SLP performing a horizontal reduction vectorization and an additional         │
│ insert/shuffle optimization, marking a number of scalar instructions and      │
│ insertelements for deletion. At destruction time, the pass iterates           │
│ DeletedInstructions, drops references for each, and then erases them from the │
│ parent. The assertion expects use_empty() but one instruction (%3 =           │
│ shufflevector ...) still has a user at that point.                            │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The debug log shows:                                                          │
│ - SLP builds and schedules bundles, then performs vectorization. It replaces  │
│ uses in a number of places and marks many instructions for deletion (via      │
│ eraseInstruction and removeInstructionsAndOperands).                          │
│ - During the insertelement shuffle optimization, it creates a new             │
│ vector/shuffle and marks insertelement chain nodes with eraseInstruction(IE). │
│ Later removeInstructionsAndOperands(RemovedInsts) marks and removes scalar    │
│ nodes.                                                                        │
│ - The log shows "Replaced:" messages and then removal staging.                │
│ - The crash happens in BoUpSLP::~BoUpSLP when erasing the                     │
│ DeletedInstructions. In the debugger, the failing instruction I is a          │
│ shufflevector (named %3) with getNumUses() == 1, located in bb1, i.e., it     │
│ still has a user.                                                             │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ The destructor currently asserts that every instruction in                    │
│ DeletedInstructions has no remaining uses (use_empty()). This is valid if all │
│ users have been either replaced or themselves marked and processed for        │
│ deletion. Elsewhere in the pass (removeInstructionsAndOperands), LLVM         │
│ accounts for the case where an instruction being deleted may still be         │
│ referenced by other instructions also slated for deletion, by asserting a     │
│ weaker condition:                                                             │
│   assert(I->use_empty() || all_of(I->uses(), [&](Use &U) { return             │
│ isDeleted(cast<Instruction>(U.getUser())); }))                                │
│ This allows removing an instruction whose users are also in                   │
│ DeletedInstructions, and relies on a later pass to null out operands and      │
│ delete in order.                                                              │
│ However, the destructor uses the stronger assertion (I->use_empty()), not     │
│ considering the legitimate case that the user is also in DeletedInstructions. │
│ In this reproducer, a shuffle left in DeletedInstructions still has a user    │
│ also marked for deletion, causing the assertion to fire even though the       │
│ subsequent steps would safely clean up.                                       │
│ Thus, the issue is an overly strict assertion and deletion logic in the       │
│ destructor that doesn't mirror the logic used by                              │
│ removeInstructionsAndOperands. The first transformation point identified is   │
│ actually the erasure in the destructor; the mismatch in conditions is the     │
│ source of failure.                                                            │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ Modify BoUpSLP::~BoUpSLP at lines 4439-4443 to relax the assertion and use    │
│ removeFromParent/SE->forgetValue similar to removeInstructionsAndOperands.    │
│ Specifically:                                                                 │
│ - Replace the current assert(I->use_empty()) with a condition that allows     │
│ uses by instructions that are also marked for deletion.                       │
│ - Use removeFromParent (not eraseFromParent) after dropAllReferences, and     │
│ forget the value in ScalarEvolution to maintain analysis correctness.         │
│                                                                               │
│ Edit:                                                                         │
│ 4439:   for (auto *I : DeletedInstructions) {                                 │
│ 4440:     assert((I->use_empty() || all_of(I->uses(), [&](Use &U) {           │
│ 4441:               return                                                    │
│ DeletedInstructions.contains(cast<Instruction>(U.getUser()));                 │
│ 4442:             })) && "trying to erase instruction with users.");          │
│ 4443:     if (I->getParent()) { I->removeFromParent(); SE->forgetValue(I); }  │
│ else { /* no parent, nothing to remove */ }                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ This change mirrors the robust handling already used in                       │
│ removeInstructionsAndOperands and prevents the destructor from asserting in   │
│ the legitimate case where users are also scheduled for deletion. The          │
│ dropAllReferences performed earlier ensures operands are cleared and allows   │
│ the recursive DCE that follows to safely clean up remaining dead              │
│ instructions.                                                                 │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ By aligning the destructor's deletion logic with the established              │
│ removeInstructionsAndOperands semantics, we avoid the false-positive          │
│ assertion in cases where a to-be-deleted instruction still has users that are │
│ also to be deleted. This ensures safe cleanup without compromising the        │
│ invariant that no live users remain. The expected effect is that the pass     │
│ cleans up DeadInsts and DeletedInstructions without crashing on the given     │
│ reproducer, while preserving correctness and analyses.                        │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
│                                                                               │
